SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION—Urging the Citizens’ Stamp
Advisory Committee and the Postmaster General of the
United States Postal Service for the creation of a postage
stamp commemorating John “Snowshoe” Thompson.
1 WHEREAS, Jon Torsteinson-Rue, more widely known as John
2 “Snowshoe” Thompson, was born in Norway in 1827 and arrived in
3 California in 1851 where he began work as a miner; and
4 WHEREAS, After his attempts at mining failed, Mr. Thompson
5 moved to Placerville, California and took up farming; and
6 WHEREAS, In 1855, Mr. Thompson saw an ad in the Sacramento
7 Union which read “People Lost to the World: Uncle Sam Needs
8 Carrier” and began working as a mail carrier; and
9 WHEREAS, Previous postmen had difficulty traversing the snow-
10 covered Sierra until Mr. Thompson carved a pair of “ski-skates”
11 fashioned after the ski-shaped snowshoes he remembered from his
12 childhood days in Norway and earned the nickname “Snowshoe”;
13 and
14 WHEREAS, Twice a month every winter from 1856 to 1876,
15 Snowshoe Thompson made the daunting and danger-filled 3-day
16 trek from Placerville, California, to Mormon Station, Nevada, later
17 renamed Genoa, and, upon delivery of his cargo and preparation of
